00:13:57.020 --> 00:13:59.930
is actually dramatically
different between summer

00:13:59.930 --> 00:14:03.674
and winter and so forth.

00:14:03.674 --> 00:14:04.650
OK.

00:14:04.650 --> 00:14:10.250
And then I want to finish
with one project that

00:14:10.250 --> 00:14:11.600
is very interesting to us.

00:14:11.600 --> 00:14:16.760
So before the awful
winter we had last year,

00:14:16.760 --> 00:14:18.450
there was another
winter that was not

00:14:18.450 --> 00:14:19.960
nearly as mild as this one.

00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:22.750
I'm so happy about this winter.

00:14:22.750 --> 00:14:25.730
And so Martin and I were
thinking, you know, weather,

00:14:25.730 --> 00:14:28.560
is there anything we
can do with weather?

00:14:28.560 --> 00:14:31.720
And we decided there's a lot
of-- there are tons of data

00:14:31.720 --> 00:14:33.230
about wind, about weather.

00:14:33.230 --> 00:14:35.630
Is there anything
interesting we can do?

00:14:35.630 --> 00:14:38.930
Well, the truth is,
wind has been visualized

00:14:38.930 --> 00:14:40.540
for hundreds of years, right?

00:14:40.540 --> 00:14:43.100
And so these are sort of
traditional visualizations

00:14:43.100 --> 00:14:44.630
of the wind.

00:14:44.630 --> 00:14:47.950
And they tended to be static
and sort of like vector

00:14:47.950 --> 00:14:51.120
field-based, right?

00:14:51.120 --> 00:14:53.750
And so you do get a
sense of direction.

00:14:53.750 --> 00:14:56.050
You do, by the
length of each arrow,

00:14:56.050 --> 00:14:58.910
you do get a sense of speed.

00:14:58.910 --> 00:15:01.600
But still, it's hard to
get a gestalt, right,

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:04.140
to get an overview and
sort of like, oh yeah,

00:15:04.140 --> 00:15:08.150
this is where there's a little
round thing going over here.

00:15:08.150 --> 00:15:14.750
This is where there's a
major pattern and so forth.

00:15:14.750 --> 00:15:18.580
So we decided to play
with this idea of,

00:15:18.580 --> 00:15:21.550
even though wind has been
visualized for hundreds

00:15:21.550 --> 00:15:24.630
of years, is there anything we
can do that's new on the web,

00:15:24.630 --> 00:15:27.230
and that is more
dynamic or feels more

00:15:27.230 --> 00:15:31.560
like this movement of the wind?

00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:35.410
And so let me show you
what we ended up doing.

00:15:38.370 --> 00:15:40.070
So this is the wind map.

00:15:40.070 --> 00:15:45.820
It's a live visualization of
the wind over the US right now.

00:15:45.820 --> 00:15:48.170
And it's public, and
it's always there.

00:15:48.170 --> 00:15:53.070
And by keeping a
lot of the detail,

00:15:53.070 --> 00:15:57.000
by not averaging everything
out into a vector field,

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:02.530
and keeping animation, you
do get a much more texture

00:16:02.530 --> 00:16:06.080
sense of the wind, and how
there are these broad strokes

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:07.350
in the middle of the country.

00:16:07.350 --> 00:16:11.300
But then, how over here in the
West, even though we're not

00:16:11.300 --> 00:16:15.220
showing you anything
about the way the land is,

00:16:15.220 --> 00:16:20.520
you can still see the tracery
of the mountains there.

00:16:20.520 --> 00:16:26.560
And then you can start to
play with this and zoom in.

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:28.510
And you can see here Boston.

00:16:28.510 --> 00:16:33.010
And we're doing great, because
we're not having too much wind.

00:16:33.010 --> 00:16:34.990
And wind is coming
from the south

00:16:34.990 --> 00:16:37.120
up, which is awesome,
because it makes

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:40.390
for that nice warm weather.

00:16:40.390 --> 00:16:42.830
But then another thing
that was interesting to us

00:16:42.830 --> 00:16:47.190
is just how much the
wind changes day to day.

00:16:47.190 --> 00:16:51.010
So we ended up creating
a small gallery

00:16:51.010 --> 00:16:53.310
of different days of wind.

00:16:53.310 --> 00:16:57.080
And so you get things
like this, where

00:16:57.080 --> 00:17:01.280
this is a day where, like,
Canada was stealing our air,

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:06.260
and not even the mountains
were stopping them.

00:17:06.260 --> 00:17:08.480
And this is very unusual.

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:12.440
This is a very
different kind of day.

00:17:12.440 --> 00:17:20.099
You also have days
like these, where

00:17:20.099 --> 00:17:23.160
there's a lot of stuff
going on in different parts

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:25.579
of the country.

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:29.960
And you just-- you know,
it's like the wind parts

00:17:29.960 --> 00:17:32.650
in different ways, sort
of how you part your hair

00:17:32.650 --> 00:17:33.540
different days.

00:17:33.540 --> 00:17:39.850
And then you have
stuff like this,

00:17:39.850 --> 00:17:46.460
where you start zooming in
and this is Hurricane Isaac

00:17:46.460 --> 00:17:48.690
making landfall.

00:17:48.690 --> 00:17:52.260
And because this is a
real-time visualization,

00:17:52.260 --> 00:17:54.030
this was running,
and we were starting

00:17:54.030 --> 00:17:56.700
to get emails from people.

00:17:56.700 --> 00:17:59.420
Like I remember this
one person said,

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:01.319
I live here in New
Orleans, and I'm

00:18:01.319 --> 00:18:03.110
looking at your
visualization, and I'm just

00:18:03.110 --> 00:18:08.060
praying that this thing just
stops, just blows over us

00:18:08.060 --> 00:18:09.160
and we're OK.

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:11.080
And that was a really
powerful moment,

00:18:11.080 --> 00:18:13.630
because we had never
had a visualization that

00:18:13.630 --> 00:18:18.950
was real-time, where
seeing this felt so--

00:18:18.950 --> 00:18:23.480
made us connect to people in
different parts of the country.

00:18:23.480 --> 00:18:32.710
It wasn't until we had this guy
that we realized what it meant.

00:18:32.710 --> 00:18:36.600
So this was Sandy
also making landfall.

00:18:36.600 --> 00:18:40.420
And for this-- you know, for the
first time we were in the path.

00:18:40.420 --> 00:18:45.690
And so this was interesting
because it was a visualization

00:18:45.690 --> 00:18:47.570
that sort of could be scary.

00:18:47.570 --> 00:18:51.570
We had never had this
situation before.

00:18:51.570 --> 00:18:54.580
And so I want to tell you a
little bit about the reaction

00:18:54.580 --> 00:18:59.670
that we got for
this visualization.

00:18:59.670 --> 00:19:04.260
Oh, yeah, and the other thing
that-- just because that's

00:19:04.260 --> 00:19:06.904
my-- that's what I
do, I visualize data,

00:19:06.904 --> 00:19:09.070
one of the things that I
think is really interesting

00:19:09.070 --> 00:19:15.340
is the data on these images
is exactly the same data as

00:19:15.340 --> 00:19:17.710
on these images, right?

00:19:17.710 --> 00:19:22.130
And so the way in which
you approach something

00:19:22.130 --> 00:19:24.317
makes a big difference.

00:19:24.317 --> 00:19:26.150
One of the things that
we're not doing here,

00:19:26.150 --> 00:19:28.100
that we're trying,
striving to do here,

00:19:28.100 --> 00:19:32.320
is to show as much detail
of the data as possible,

00:19:32.320 --> 00:19:35.400
to not aggregate the
data as much as possible.

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:37.650
And that has a
bunch of pitfalls,

00:19:37.650 --> 00:19:41.670
because it could create a much
more complex visualization

00:19:41.670 --> 00:19:43.540
than people can understand.

00:19:43.540 --> 00:19:45.880
But in a fascinating
way, I would

00:19:45.880 --> 00:19:48.570
say that the complexity,
the visual complexity

00:19:48.570 --> 00:19:51.580
of these pictures here,
actually helps your eyes.

00:19:51.580 --> 00:19:55.120
It's sort of like when you have
more pixels in your camera,

00:19:55.120 --> 00:19:56.682
it just, like, focuses.

00:19:56.682 --> 00:19:58.140
To me, it's sort
of the same thing.

00:19:58.140 --> 00:20:03.980
It's like, oh finally, I can
see these broad patterns of wind

00:20:03.980 --> 00:20:10.350
that, actually now, seeing them
all at once makes sense to me.

00:20:10.350 --> 00:20:12.460
So we started getting
a lot of email.

00:20:12.460 --> 00:20:13.120
A lot.

00:20:13.120 --> 00:20:16.260
Like, we have never gotten
this much email before.

00:20:16.260 --> 00:20:18.620
And so it turns
out that farmers--

00:20:18.620 --> 00:20:20.030
we did this as an art piece.

00:20:20.030 --> 00:20:21.590
We just put it on
the web, and we

00:20:21.590 --> 00:20:24.825
thought it was going to be this
completely sort of niche thing.

00:20:24.825 --> 00:20:26.930
It was like, who cares
about wind, right?

00:20:26.930 --> 00:20:30.780
I didn't before I did
this visualization.

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:32.710
But it turns out a
ton of people do.

00:20:32.710 --> 00:20:35.460
So farmers will look
at this visualization

00:20:35.460 --> 00:20:39.050
before spraying their crops.

00:20:39.050 --> 00:20:41.440
Scientists will look
at the visualization

00:20:41.440 --> 00:20:44.760
for bird migration, for
butterfly migration.

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:47.440
Teachers love to
show this to kids,

00:20:47.440 --> 00:20:51.720
and to try to sit with them and
try to think about forecasts,

00:20:51.720 --> 00:20:55.510
weather forecasts
and is this a week

00:20:55.510 --> 00:20:59.310
that's prone to tornadoes,
and things like that.

00:20:59.310 --> 00:21:04.410
Pilots started looking at this
visualization before flying.

00:21:04.410 --> 00:21:08.070
And then when we started-- both
commercial and military pilots,

00:21:08.070 --> 00:21:08.730
by the way.

00:21:08.730 --> 00:21:11.165
And so when we got those
emails about the pilots,

00:21:11.165 --> 00:21:14.970
we're like, whoa,
whoa, no, no, no.

00:21:14.970 --> 00:21:18.620
Do not look at this map
before you fly your plane.

00:21:18.620 --> 00:21:22.780
We very specifically say that
we are showing surface wind,

00:21:22.780 --> 00:21:23.280
right?

00:21:23.280 --> 00:21:27.420
So surface wind is from the
earth to, like, 10 meters.

00:21:27.420 --> 00:21:30.320
It's like, you're going to
fly your plane way above that.

00:21:30.320 --> 00:21:31.920
And that's not going
to be the wind.

00:21:31.920 --> 00:21:32.735
They know that.

00:21:32.735 --> 00:21:33.360
They know that.

00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:37.140
But it just got a little
bit too scary for us.

00:21:37.140 --> 00:21:42.010
Like, wildfire firefighters
would look at the visualization

00:21:42.010 --> 00:21:44.980
before deciding
on their strategy.

00:21:44.980 --> 00:21:50.810
And so something that started
as our curiosity about the wind

00:21:50.810 --> 00:21:53.710
ended up being a
utilitarian tool for people

00:21:53.710 --> 00:21:54.700
without us knowing.

00:21:54.700 --> 00:21:56.600
And it is great.

00:21:56.600 --> 00:21:59.680
At the same time, you feel
like you're on the hook,

00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:03.900
because what if your
visualization isn't right?

00:22:03.900 --> 00:22:06.740
So we put a disclaimer.

00:22:06.740 --> 00:22:10.540
We said, do not use this
map for flying a plane,

00:22:10.540 --> 00:22:12.380
sailing a boat, or
fight wildfires,

00:22:12.380 --> 00:22:16.050
because we got multiple emails
about each one of those things.

00:22:16.050 --> 00:22:19.040
And we thought, OK, just
FYI, we have this disclaimer.

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:21.320
Then we started getting
emails where they're like,

00:22:21.320 --> 00:22:24.210
we understand that
it's your thing,

00:22:24.210 --> 00:22:28.450
but respect the power
of the visualization.

00:22:28.450 --> 00:22:35.160
And so this just, to me, is
a really interesting moment,

00:22:35.160 --> 00:22:38.920
because what it tells
me is that we are coming

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:42.300
in an interesting
other end of the arc

00:22:42.300 --> 00:22:44.710
I was talking to
you about before.

00:22:44.710 --> 00:22:47.340
When I started
working in this field,

00:22:47.340 --> 00:22:51.870
we were very much in the this
is scientific, for scientists

00:22:51.870 --> 00:22:54.200
only, for experts only.

00:22:54.200 --> 00:22:58.030
And now, I am so
proud that we have

00:22:58.030 --> 00:23:01.710
ways of talking about
data, of looking at data

00:23:01.710 --> 00:23:05.930
where we're embracing so many
more communities, where it's

00:23:05.930 --> 00:23:08.010
not about whether
you're doing science

00:23:08.010 --> 00:23:10.780
or not, or whether about you're
running a government or not,

00:23:10.780 --> 00:23:12.790
but it is about
your life, right?

00:23:12.790 --> 00:23:15.400
It's how you
appropriate the data.

00:23:15.400 --> 00:23:17.150
How do you make use of it?

00:23:17.150 --> 00:23:20.410
How do you become a better
consumer, a more skeptical

00:23:20.410 --> 00:23:22.320
consumer of data?

00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:25.110
And so that's what excites
me about this kind of work.

00:23:25.110 --> 00:23:29.640
It's sort of like how can
we use these powers, right?

00:23:29.640 --> 00:23:36.350
How can we use data for our
own benefits as citizens,

00:23:36.350 --> 00:23:39.010
and become better at it?

00:23:39.010 --> 00:23:42.640
And I think visualization can
play an awesome role there.

