things about your data,

00:27:28.230 --> 00:27:30.660
verbalization
meaning we will say

00:27:30.660 --> 00:27:33.720
things that are of
interest about your data.

00:27:33.720 --> 00:27:35.590
So we started
saying things like,

00:27:35.590 --> 00:27:39.900
oh, this is growing
exponentially, by 2%.

00:27:39.900 --> 00:27:44.190
And then we realized that lay
users do not understand that.

00:27:44.190 --> 00:27:46.710
What do you mean, an
exponential growth of 2%?

00:27:46.710 --> 00:27:50.040
An exponential growth is
an explosive growth, right?

00:27:50.040 --> 00:27:57.870
So we had to reword things
because our jargon was not

00:27:57.870 --> 00:28:00.840
making sense to end users.

00:28:00.840 --> 00:28:04.090
I would say another thing
that we did a long time ago,

00:28:04.090 --> 00:28:07.090
we created-- this
was not at Google,

00:28:07.090 --> 00:28:09.290
this was when I was at IBM.

00:28:09.290 --> 00:28:12.100
We created the
first website where

00:28:12.100 --> 00:28:15.320
anyone could come
upload data and create

00:28:15.320 --> 00:28:18.610
interactive visualizations
of their data and share

00:28:18.610 --> 00:28:20.110
with others.

00:28:20.110 --> 00:28:24.730
And when we presented that at
the top academic conference

00:28:24.730 --> 00:28:27.160
on visualization, on
data visualization,

00:28:27.160 --> 00:28:29.750
it was a half and half split.

00:28:29.750 --> 00:28:33.810
Some people were really excited
about the ability of giving--

00:28:33.810 --> 00:28:36.640
of making this technology
available to end users,

00:28:36.640 --> 00:28:40.840
to anyone without training, and
half of the people were like,

00:28:40.840 --> 00:28:42.430
are you crazy?

00:28:42.430 --> 00:28:45.580
How dare you put these
visualization techniques

00:28:45.580 --> 00:28:47.820
in the hands of non-experts.

00:28:47.820 --> 00:28:49.610
They're going to mislead.

00:28:49.610 --> 00:28:52.070
They're going to come up
with the wrong conclusions.

00:28:52.070 --> 00:28:55.560
They're going to visualize
the data in the wrong way.

00:28:55.560 --> 00:28:57.850
To which I say, let them.

00:28:57.850 --> 00:29:01.970
Because if we don't make
these tools available,

00:29:01.970 --> 00:29:04.190
then people are
not going to learn.

00:29:04.190 --> 00:29:07.720
I want people to make
little mistakes with data,

00:29:07.720 --> 00:29:11.330
play with things, before they
make big mistakes with data

00:29:11.330 --> 00:29:15.050
at government or at industry.

00:29:15.050 --> 00:29:20.380
I want to have a pipeline where
kids-- so in this website, kids

00:29:20.380 --> 00:29:22.600
were playing with data, right?

00:29:22.600 --> 00:29:24.330
And that's the kind
of pipeline that I

00:29:24.330 --> 00:29:28.460
think is important for you to
grow as a consumer of data,

00:29:28.460 --> 00:29:31.090
as a consumer of
data visualization.

00:29:31.090 --> 00:29:33.480
You have to become more skilled.

00:29:33.480 --> 00:29:35.390
And the only way
to become skilled--

00:29:35.390 --> 00:29:37.370
I think one of the
most effective ways

00:29:37.370 --> 00:29:39.970
is to play with it
yourself, right?

00:29:39.970 --> 00:29:43.060
So yes, I'm sure people
will make mistakes.

00:29:43.060 --> 00:29:45.260
But I welcome them,
right, before they

00:29:45.260 --> 00:29:46.442
become big mistakes.

00:29:46.442 --> 00:29:47.650
Like, I want little mistakes.

